{"id":"2106.06116","submitter":"Marcus Prado","authors":"Marcus Prado, Fabrizio Sgrignuoli, Yuyao Chen, Luca Dal Negro, Felipe\n  A. Pinheiro","title":"Structural entropy and spatial decay of quasimodes in Vogel spirals","comments":"8 pages, 3 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. B 104, 184204 (2021)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.104.184204","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.dis-nn physics.optics","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We investigate the spatial decay and temporal localization properties of\nquasimodes (i.e., scattering resonances) of two-dimensional Vogel spirals,\ncomposed of deterministic, aperiodic arrays of electric dipoles. By determining\nthe structural entropy and localization maps of Vogel spirals using the Green's\nmatrix method, we show that three distinctive decay types of quasimodes coexist\nin Vogel spirals: exponential, power-law, and Gaussian. While the exponential\nand the power-law decays typically occur in disordered media and multifractal\nsystems, respectively, the Gaussian decay is demonstrated to characterize, on\naverage, the most localized quasimodes of Vogel spirals, both spatially\n(smallest participation ratios) and temporarily (longest lifetimes). These\ndecay forms are demonstrated by a no-fitting analysis of the localization maps,\nindependently corroborated by calculating the electric field in real space,\nwhich also provides a direct evidence of the algebraic spatial decay of\ncritical quasimodes. Altogether our findings unveil a rich spectrum of both\nlong-lived and spatially localized quasimodes that coexist in Vogel spirals and\ncan be of direct relevance to novel optical functionalities for applications to\nlight sources and sensing devices.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 11 Jun 2021 01:41:41 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 19 Aug 2021 12:59:40 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 11 Oct 2021 21:29:38 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-12-01"}
