{"id":"2106.06264","submitter":"Fabio Lucio Toninelli","authors":"Giuseppe Cannizzaro, Levi Haunschmid-Sibitz, Fabio Toninelli","title":"$\\sqrt{\\log t}$-superdiffusivity for a Brownian particle in the curl of\n  the 2d GFF","comments":"to appear on Annals of Probability. v3: several proofs simplified,\n  main result sharpened. 23 pages","journal-ref":"Annals of Probability 2022, Vol. 50, No. 6, 2475-2498","doi":"10.1214/22-AOP1589","report-no":null,"categories":"math.PR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The present work is devoted to the study of the large time behaviour of a\ncritical Brownian diffusion in two dimensions, whose drift is divergence-free,\nergodic and given by the curl of the 2-dimensional Gaussian Free Field. We\nprove the conjecture, made in [B. T\\'oth, B. Valk\\'o, J. Stat. Phys., 2012],\naccording to which the diffusion coefficient $D(t)$ diverges as $\\sqrt{\\log t}$\nfor $t\\to\\infty$. Starting from the fundamental work by Alder and Wainwright\n[B. Alder, T. Wainright, Phys. Rev. Lett. 1967], logarithmically superdiffusive\nbehaviour has been predicted to occur for a wide variety of out-of-equilibrium\nsystems in the critical spatial dimension $d=2$. Examples include the diffusion\nof a tracer particle in a fluid, self-repelling polymers and random walks,\nBrownian particles in divergence-free random environments, and, more recently,\nthe 2-dimensional critical Anisotropic KPZ equation. Even if in all of these\ncases it is expected that $D(t)\\sim\\sqrt{\\log t}$, to the best of the authors'\nknowledge, this is the first instance in which such precise asymptotics is\nrigorously established.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 11 Jun 2021 09:31:10 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 16 Jun 2021 13:20:55 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 10 Jun 2022 07:29:09 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-11-04"}
